法規內容.條文內容:
Any passenger ship navigating abroad may only depart from the domestic port where she calls after she is inspected and 
verified by the inspector of the shipping administration authority on the following:
1. Various certificates are valid;
2. Lifesaving, fire extinguishing and rescue facilities are readily prepared;
3. Hull, and machinery are in normal state;  
4. The facilities for light, ventilation, sanitation, drinking water, and food comply with requirements;
5. The passenger List is complete and shows none of excessive number of passengers are carried on board;
6. The category and quantity of cargoes carried concurrently comply with requirements and the cargoes are suitably stowed; 
and
7. The stowage and ballast make the proper stability available at all times for the ship.

The shipping administration authority may only inspect Item 1, 5, 6 and 7 in the previous paragraph, while makes the spot 
inspection on the rest items before the departure of a passenger ship navigating the shorter international route.

Safety shall be ensured adequately for the locations, passages and constructions of passenger cabins, and the spaces between 
them and other compartments; such passenger cabins shall be isolated from cold, heat, noise and odor. The following places 
shall in no case be used for passenger cabins:
1. The lowest point of the cabin's top deck is below the max load line;
2. The places before collision bulkheads or, if without such bulkhead, the places before the line that is a half of the max ship 
width from the inside of the bow stem on the upper deck;
3. The places less than 60 cm in width or length;
4. The places wherein the net height is less than 182cm; however, for the passenger ship navigating coastal, inland water or 
shorter inland water route, the height may be reduced to 140cm if the shipping administration authority deems that there will be 
no obstruction to escape when in emergency;
5. The places within 60 cm of the outer circumference of boiler spaces where heat insulation is not provided; and
6. Other places where the shipping administration authority deems unsuitable for passenger dwelling and activities.

Passenger cabins of a passenger ship navigating through the frigid zone shall be equipped with efficient heating equipment; 
however, such equipment may be exempted if the shipping administration authority deems unnecessary, or they practicably 
cannot be equipped in the ship.

The fixed or movable berths in steerage cabins shall be arranged and sized in accordance with the following requirements:
1. The number of tiers of berth shall not be more than three;
2. When two berths are placed side by side, a partition board of at least 45cm in height shall be installed. When using either of 
them, there will be no need to cross over the other;
3. The top of the lower berth of a double-tier one shall have a height of no less than 30cm above the floor; the height between 
the tops of the upper and the lower, berth and the overhead space above the top of the upper berth shall be no less than 76cm;
4. The top of the lower tier of a triple-tier berth shall have a height of no less than 30cm above the floor. The height between the 
tops of the lower and the middle or the middle and the upper, or the overhead space above the top of the upper shall be no less 
than 66cm;
5. The length of the inner edge of the berth shall be no less than 180cm, and the width, no less than 53cm; and 
6. The movable berths shall be installed with seat braces, which shall be firmly secured with bolts or other methods.

Reclining chairs in steerage cabins shall be arranged and sized as follows:
1. One chair for one passenger only;
2. The chairs shall have arms, and the backrests that shall be easily adjusted backward to recline properly;
3. The width and depth of the inner edges of chair shall be no less than 50cm and 55cm for the international passenger ship, 
and no less than 45cm and 48cm for the domestic passenger ship;
4. The space in front of the chair shall be no less than 35cm;
5. The distance between the side of the aisle and the center of any chair shall not exceed 2m; and
6. The chairs shall be secured on decks, making them not to move due to rolling or pitching of the ship.

The board and matting ground berths in steerage cabins shall comply with the following requirements:
1. The ground berths shall be at least 10cm in height from the top of deck;
2. The overhead space of the berths shall be kept at least 170cm, but may be properly reduced if approved by the shipping 
administration authority;
3. The distance between the side of aisle and the center of the farthest berth shall not exceed 370cm; and
4. The berths shall be firmly secured to avoid floating due to flooding.

Chairs and benches in steerage cabin shall be arranged and sized as follows:
1. The depth of inner edges shall be no less than 40cm;
2. Except that the benches may be provided for a route of less than three hours, any chair shall have proper arms and a 
backrest, and with one chair for each passenger only; 
3. The width of the inner edges of a chair and bench that passenger occupies shall be no less than the requirements as follows:
(1) For a voyage of less than one and a half hours: 40cm;
(2) For a voyage of one and a half hours up to less than six hours: 45cm; 
(3) For a voyage of six hours up to less than twenty four hours: 50cm;
4. The space in front of chairs and benches shall be no less than 30cm;
5. The distance between the center of the farthest seat and the aisle shall not exceed 2m; and
6. The chairs and benches shall be firmly secured to avoid moving due to rolling or pitching of the ship.

The upper decks and other unenclosed places of a passenger ship shall not be included for computing the certified number of 
passengers. However, the passenger ship that navigates in the coastal, inland water and shorter inland water route and is 
approved to carry deck passengers by the shipping administration authority, which deems that there is no fear for severe sea 
conditions, may include said places for the computation. Nonetheless, the following places shall be excluded: 
1. The areas of hatches, skylights, ship-side drains or other obstructions;
2. The places between deckhouses, hatches, skylights and ship-side drains, with a width less than 60cm; 
3. Forecastle decks;
4. The upper deck or forecastle deck between the bow stem and the place one-eighth of ships length from the stem; 
5. Any place where the shipping administration authority deems necessary to be used for gathering passengers when in 
emergency; and
6. Any place where the shipping administration authority deems inappropriate for carrying passengers.

Any passenger is not allowed to board a passenger ship unless he holds a valid passenger tickets, however, except the 
following passengers:
1. Children under one year of age, who board an international passenger ship together with their custodians;
2. Children under three years of age, who board a domestic passenger ship together with their custodians;
3. Passengers holding party carriage contract;
4. Passengers of the ferryboats that are approved by shipping administration authority to exempt from issuing passenger 
tickets; and
5. Other passengers who are approved by the shipping administration authority.

The assigned duties mentioned in the preceding article shall include:
1. Shutting side scuttles, watertight doors, fire doors, drain ports, and all   sewage or other discharge holes on shell plates 
below the bulkhead deck line of compartment;
2. Stopping fans and ventilation systems;
3. Operating all lifesaving, fire fighting, lights, sound signals, flag signals, and rescue equipment;
4. Preparing and launching lifeboats, life rafts and other lifesaving equipment; 
5. Fire patrolling and extinguishing fires;
6. Designating deck crew to assemble passengers and pay attention to:
(1) giving passenger warnings;
(2) inspecting passengers' clothes, footwear, and life vests to ensure
that they have donned suitably;  
(3) gathering passengers and directing them to the places where they shall be;
(4) directing passengers to move and keeping order in the passageways and on the stairways;
(5) helping the old, the weak, women and children passengers as much as possible; and  
(6) checking if blankets are taken to the survival craft.
7. Appointing specific persons to keep the portable radio equipment;
8. Designating rescue team and setting up damage control center; 
9. Designating qualified life-saving crew to take charge of operation of each survival craft; and 
10. Any task with regard to emergency that the master deems necessary.

Each lifeboat shall be manned with qualified crewmembers based on the carrying capacity of persons as follows: 
1. For the capacity of under 41: two members;
2. For the capacity of 41 and under 62: three members;
3. For the capacity of 62 and under 86: four members; or
4. For the capacity of 86 and over: five members.

The present Regulations do not apply to the following non-commercial ships, which shall be otherwise subject to the 
administrative rules the shipping administration authority may prescribe depending on the following characteristics of such 
ships:
1. Pleasure boats; 
2. Governmental non-commercial ships;
3. Commuting ships,
4. Medical ships;
5. Fishing ships or industrial factory ships; 
6. Requisitioned ships for military purpose; and
7. Special ships approved by MOTC subject to the proposals of shipping administration authorities.
